{"ts":"2026-06-27T05:03:36.888Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Discovering Next.js Quirks**\n\nI've just stumbled upon a crucial detail: this isn't standard Next.js! It's version 16.2.9, which has significant breaking changes impacting APIs, conventions, and file structure. My initial assumptions are off-base, so I need to consult the guide within node_modules/next/dist/docs/ immediately. This necessitates a whole new approach to the analysis, and I'll adapt accordingly.\n\n\n**Refining Support Center Strategy**\n\nI'm now focusing on the 'app/portal/support/page.tsx' file. I realize that for the support center, we need to design a high-fidelity state management block. The core requirements for the ticket list, creation form, and filtering capabilities are solidifying. I'm prioritizing a calm, secure UI with excellent mobile support, and I will be using standard React, TypeScript, and Tailwind. I'm planning frontend-only ticket creation and linting as a priority. I'm detailing out the specific support ticket fields and will ensure no imports are broken.\n\n\n**Analyzing Ticket Schema Details**\n\nI'm now diving into the `SupportTicket` schema, specifically the properties: `title`, `status`, `priority`, `category`, `project`, `createdAt`, `desc`, and `replies`. I've outlined the data types for each, and it's looking good, but there's a wrinkle! The initial tickets, loaded from `previewSupportTickets`, may not perfectly align with these defined types. I need to examine `lib/mock-data-model.ts` to see what is happening!\n\n\n**Enhancing Mock Data Strategy**\n\nI'm now focused on enriching the mock ticket data. I realized I can dynamically add or define a local rich dataset, and I'm leaning toward the latter. I'm ensuring each ticket has both a category and a linked project for robust filtering. Defining a local state starting from an enhanced mock version allows for more accurate filtering right from the beginning, and I'm verifying the ticket categories, priority, and status options.\n\n\n**Defining Project Link Options**\n\nI'm now identifying linked projects. I've extracted the project options, either from `previewProjects` or by hardcoding/deriving them. The list is set: \"Sovereign Core Sandbox 02\", \"Model Guardrail Sandbox 04\", \"Sovereign Mining Intel Loop\", \"Federal Ledger Enclave Alpha\", and \"General - No Project\". The next step is to design a custom UI.\nI am focused on the title and description, a status shield or lock, and a top stats hud with four wide cards. I will refine the filter and action bar, prioritizing a premium \"Create Ticket\" button on mobile.\n\n\n**Designing UI for Tickets**\n\nI am now structuring the UI for tickets. On the desktop, I'm envisioning a scrollable sidebar with ticket cards that become active on click, each displaying ID, timestamp, title, and badges for status, priority, and category. The main area will show a ticket's console with ID, title, linked project, category, telemetry, description, and an interactive thread, including reply functionality. I'm ensuring mobile-first design with a top segment selector for focused views: feed, active thread, or new ticket.\n\n\n**Confirming File Dependencies**\n\nI'm now confirming our file dependencies and Next.js version 16 compatibility. I'm focusing on the imports in `app/portal/support/page.tsx` and verifying we can use standard React hooks, lucide-react icons, and Tailwind CSS. I'm confirming all categories: `Project Delivery`, `AI Operations`, `Billing`, `Documents`, `Access`, `Governance`, `General`. I'm confirming that we can import from `@/lib/mock-data-model`.\n\n\n**Defining Filter Options**\n\nI'm now detailing the filter options, starting with state and mocking dynamic dataset construction. My current focus is on building the data model and state for the support center UI, and I'm ensuring comprehensive filter options are available. The supported filter fields now include `priority`, `category`, `linked project`, and `status`. I will now start adding the filtering implementation into the UI.\n\n\n**Constructing Ticket Creation Form**\n\nI'm now designing the \"Create Ticket\" form with priority, category, and linked project options, along with subject, description, and a submit button. On submission, the form generates a new ticket with a randomized ID, sets the status to \"open,\" adds a welcome message to replies, and then adds it to the ticket list. I'm verifying the typescript interface for an enriched support ticket, and that there are no linting errors.\n\n\n\n**Populating Initial Ticket State**\n\nI'm now integrating the existing ticket data, updating `previewSupportTickets` with added properties to ensure compatibility with my defined schema. I'm adding `category`, `project`, `priority`, and `status` to the three existing tickets, and then I will merge this data with the initial state to provide the UI with an enriched, ready-to-use dataset, which will support immediate filtering and display functionalities. I'm ensuring all data types align precisely with the established interface.\n\n\n**Adding Diverse Sample Tickets**\n\nI'm now enriching the initial ticket data further. I've integrated two more sample tickets to enhance the dataset. These tickets cover diverse scenarios, with varied priorities, categories, and project associations. They include detailed descriptions and statuses like \"resolved\", which should ensure that the initial UI displays a richer range of filtering capabilities. I've made certain that the data types for these additions match the defined `SupportTicket` interface.\n\n\n**Designing Ticket Elements**\n\nI'm now focusing on specific UI elements. I need to implement a detailed design for ticket cards, ensuring a clean, modern, and professional layout. I'm adding `lucide-react` icons like `ShieldAlert`, `MessageSquare`, and `Plus`. The interface will include clear separation for each card with ID, timestamp, and badges for status, priority, and category, following the previously defined details. I need to make sure the interface is built in `app/portal/support/page.tsx` now.\n\n\n**Defining UI Colors**\n\nI'm now determining the color scheme for the ticket UI, and I am ensuring high contrast and readability. I've decided on a dark-mode theme utilizing Tailwind CSS classes, so I'm leveraging various shades of black, white, and neon-colored accents for critical visual cues. I'm focusing on ensuring intuitive visual differentiation for ticket statuses and priorities, such as using red neon for \"Critical\" and orange/amber for \"High\" priority tickets. I will be incorporating subtle gradients and borders for depth.\n\n\n**Drafting Complete Ticket Page**\n\nI'm now drafting the full code for `app/portal/support/page.tsx` with zero typos. I'm focusing on UI component integration, including ticket cards and a ticket console, and making sure the styles are all perfect. The code is clean and lint-free, ensuring robust filter and action bars. I'm double-checking the code to confirm it implements all described elements, including the color scheme and button styles, before replacing the existing file.\n\n\n**Defining Core State Elements**\n\nI'm now detailing the core state management for the ticket page, defining state variables for tickets, search queries, filter selections (priority, category, project, status), the currently active ticket ID, new reply text, and a boolean to track create mode. I'm focusing on ensuring these states are initialized correctly with data and defaults, and I'm designing a system for smooth updates, ensuring high performance.\n\n\n**Implementing Mobile Design**\n\nI'm now focusing on mobile design and adapting the UI to prioritize the \"Launch New Support Wire\" form instead of the detail panel. I'm introducing a `mobileTab` state, switching between \"feed\", \"thread\", and \"create\" views for ease of navigation. My goal is to ensure a fully responsive, clear, and robust design that works seamlessly across all devices.\n\n\n\n**Styling Filter Selectors**\n\nI'm now focusing on styling the filter `<select>` elements. I realized that to ensure a clean, custom aesthetic without looking generic, I need to use custom Tailwind classes to make the elements visually appealing. I'm adding `lucide-react` icons inside each selector for a polished and high-quality appearance, to make them stand out. I'm going to add the `lucide-react` icons now.\n\n\n**Designing Empty State Logic**\n\nI'm now implementing logic to render filtered tickets and the empty state. When no tickets match the current filters, I'll display a premium empty state illustration with a reset button. Clicking a ticket will select it, set the create mode to false, and switch to the thread tab on mobile. I'm also adding a top header to the list showing the count of filtered tickets, with a button to launch a new support wire.\n\n\n\n**Visualizing Core Components**\n\nI'm now detailing the UI of individual ticket consoles. I'm focusing on the \"Diagnostic Telemetry Box\", ensuring its log display is retro-futuristic with a dark code block. I'm planning to style each element using Tailwind. I also want to include a \"Reply Thread\", displaying replies with varying visual cues for engineers and users. I'm also adding a secure message box. I'm ensuring everything works together cleanly.\n\n\n**Visualizing Security Wire Detail**\n\nI'm now implementing the UI for the individual ticket detail, with a focus on a \"Sovereign cryptographic network node\" visual placeholder for the selected ticket, and a gorgeous graphic for the empty state. My core is now the \"Create Ticket\" form with a full implementation, with new ticket creation details. I will also be including a \"Diagnostic Telemetry Box\" styled with a dark, retro-futuristic look.\n\n\n**Verifying Form & Imports**\n\nI'm now verifying the form state variables: `newSubject`, `newDesc`, `newPriority`, `newCategory`, and `newProject` are all defined and correctly initialized within the \"create ticket\" functionality. I'm confirming all required imports are correctly referenced and there are no linting errors, focusing on components from `@/components/private-app` to avoid re-inventing the wheel.\n\n\n**Confirming Ticket Detail Page**\n\nI'm now focusing on `app/portal/support/[id]/page.tsx`, and I've confirmed that clicking a ticket works and navigates seamlessly to this existing detail view. I've decided to keep this page clean and static, and the main dashboard the interactive hub. Now I will make the navigation between these two pages more intuitive.\n\n\n**Confirming Categories & Projects**\n\nI'm now making certain of specific ticket categories and project options for the UI. I've listed ticket categories: Project Delivery, AI Operations, Billing, Documents, Access, Governance, General. And projects: Sovereign Core Sandbox 02, Model Guardrail Sandbox 04, Sovereign Mining Intel Loop, Federal Ledger Enclave Alpha, General / Non-Project. I'm verifying style standards and avoiding build errors.\n\n\n**Refactoring File Imports**\n\nI'm now refactoring import statements to improve clarity. I'm focusing on `app/portal/support/page.tsx` and verifying we're importing `previewSupportTickets` and `SupportTicket` directly from `@/lib/mock-data-model`. This approach streamlines dependencies and ensures a cleaner file structure. I'm confirming all references within the file are properly updated, reducing potential issues.\n\n\n**Designing Cryptographic Wire Visualization**\n\nI'm now integrating a custom SVG element into `app/portal/support/page.tsx` that visually represents the \"Support Wire.\" I'm designing a pulsing, animated graphic depicting a secured connection between the Client Enclave and GFF HQ, complete with eBPF interlock nodes. This should meet the UI quality requirements for visual elements. I'm focusing on ensuring it is responsive and visually compelling.\n\n\n**Implementing Client-Side State**\n\nI'm now making the support page fully client-side stateful, ensuring all data and interactions happen within the browser. I'm focusing on crafting a responsive, visual SVG element representing a secure enclave handshake, and it's looking gorgeous. I'm focusing on micro-interactions, adding a blue hover glow and subtle icon shifts, and I'm developing a high-fidelity visual feed for the \"Narrative Timeline\" inside ticket details. I'm focusing on clean micro-interactions, building a beautiful page.\n\n\n"}}
